You are working in `Kostmag`, a Next.js 15 / App Router / MDX-driven Danish supplement review site.

Priority:
1. Preserve user intent and existing rankings/slots.
2. Prefer targeted updates over broad regeneration.
3. Keep `localhost:3000` usable during work.
4. Verify user-visible output, not only data files.

Project map:
- Category pages: `src/app/(da)/kosttilskud/<category-slug>/page.mdx`
- Product pages: `src/app/(da)/kosttilskud/produkter/<product-slug>/content.mdx`
- Canonical category page spec: `docs/category-page-canonical-spec.md`
- Broken links report: `content/broken-links-report.json`
- Buy links: `content/product-buy-links.json`
- Product images: `content/product-images.json`
- Crawled product cache: `content/crawled-products/**`
- 404 replace API: `src/app/api/admin/404/replace/route.ts`
- 404 admin UI: `src/app/(da)/admin/404/Admin404Table.tsx`
- Category rebuild script: `scripts/rebuild-category-pages.ts`
- Product rewrite script: `scripts/rewrite-product-content.ts`
- Crawler entrypoint: `scripts/crawlers/crawl.ts`

Core product/content rules:
- The site uses a personal, hands-on, "tested in practice" tone. Product copy should feel grounded in real usage, not generic SEO filler.
- For category-page rebuilds, treat `docs/category-page-canonical-spec.md` as the primary source of truth for layout, ranking, frontmatter, CTA behavior, sections, and QA.
- Product titles must be cleaned when needed:
  - remove redundant quantity suffixes in display title when they make titles clumsy
  - remove incorrect brand prefixes when the product is not truly branded that way
  - keep genuine brand names when they are correct
- Button standard across category pages:
  - CTA button text is only `Til butik`
  - small toplists do NOT show the store label below the button
  - full product cards keep the store name below the button in smaller grey text
  - no underline on buttons in any state
- Intro/product count text must reflect the actual number of shown products dynamically.
- Core ranking contract for category pages:
  - visible rank 1 must be `BEDST I TEST`
  - visible rank 2 must be `BEDSTE PREMIUM`
  - visible rank 3 must be `BEDSTE BUDGET`
  - this order must stay consistent across toplists, summary, product cards, comparison table, and JSON-LD

Critical `/admin/404` replacement rules:
- A replacement is "replace in place", not "add a new product".
- Preserve the existing product slug/slot identity used on the category page.
- Preserve the ranking/order of all other products.
- Update only the relevant product-linked sections of the category page.
- Do NOT regenerate or alter intro, FAQ, buying guide, or other non-product content during a targeted 404 replacement.
- If a custom image is uploaded in admin, prefer it over remote download.
- Remove the stale broken-link row only after the replacement and category rebuild succeed.
- The UI should show stepwise progress, not one static loading state.

Current 404 architecture:
- `POST /api/admin/404/replace` starts an async job and returns a `jobId`.
- `GET /api/admin/404/replace?jobId=...` is polled for status.
- Replacement jobs are serialized through a queue in `replace/route.ts`.
- The admin table polls job status and keeps completed rows visible with DONE/hide-row behavior.

Critical category rebuild rule:
- For targeted product replacement rebuilds, always preserve non-product content.
- Use `scripts/rebuild-category-pages.ts` with `--preserve-non-product-content` when the task is a 404 replacement or a single-slot product swap.
- Product rebuilds should update product cards, toplist/comparison sections, and affected product sections only.

Crawler and parsing rules:
- Crawl the new URL before switching buy links so failure does not corrupt the live page.
- Do not trust a URL blindly just because it returns 200. Some stores can resolve to the wrong product.
- Validate crawled content semantically against the requested URL/product before declaring success.
- If the crawled result is obviously a different product, abort the replacement instead of publishing bad content.
- Bodylab, Healthwell, CoreNutrition and similar stores may have redirect/discontinued quirks; verify the actual rendered product title/content.

Known pitfalls to avoid:
- Never let internal-link insertion touch YAML frontmatter in MDX files.
- Do not let a targeted replacement rewrite the entire category page.
- Do not create a fresh slug just because the replacement product name changed.
- Do not mark `/admin/404` as complete before the category page actually reflects the new product.
- Do not assume the broken-links report is perfectly current; when matching a row, fall back by slug, old URL, or position.

When the user says "continue" after a long session:
- First verify the dev server on `localhost:3000`.
- Then inspect whether the relevant `/admin/404` row still exists.
- Then verify the real page output, not just the admin status.

Server/dev workflow:
- If `localhost:3000` hangs or no listener exists, cleanly restart the Next dev server and verify with an HTTP request.
- Keep the server on port `3000` when possible so local links remain valid.

Recommended verification after substantive work:
- Read lints for edited files.
- Verify affected file content.
- Verify the rendered local page on `http://localhost:3000/...`.
- For 404 replacements, verify all of:
  - `content/product-buy-links.json`
  - product `content.mdx`
  - category page render
  - `content/broken-links-report.json`

User preference summary:
- The user cares a lot about reliable `/admin/404` replacement flow.
- They prefer narrow, deterministic fixes over "smart" full-page rewrites.
- They want frequent progress updates during long tasks.
- They are sensitive to regressions caused by broad rebuilds.
